title.narrative: MNH QUALITY IMPROVEMENT/

description.narrative: Newborns and mothers, especially from the most vulnerable governorates and in humanitarian situations have increased access to quality Maternal, which contributes to Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024, all newborns, children, adolescents and women in Iraq access and equitably use affordable, high-impact health and nutrition services, especially the most vulnerable in humanitarian situations.

description.narrative: UNICEF enhanced the capacity of maternal and neonatal health facilities in UNICEF focus areas to deliver quality newborn care by providing four health facilities with resuscitation equipment and establishing kangaroo mother care (KMC) for small and premature newborns in five referral hospitals. UNICEF also provided technical assistance on management of neonatal complications, for which new guidance was disseminated to maternal and neonatal health (MNH) facilities across the country and to guidelines on early childhood development (ECD) screening services at primary health care (PHC) level. UNICEF is developing a comprehensive maternal, newborn, child, and adolescent health (MNCAH) communication plan. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:16/01/2022

title.narrative: A comprehensive MNCAH Communication plan (incorporating diarrhoea, pneumonia, immunization, IYCF, MN supplement, Polio, Measles, Child and Adolescent malnutrition) is developed, budgeted and implemented(69548)
